{"type":"message","id":"a60b71e4","parentId":"7eb1d4bf","timestamp":"2026-03-07T01:26:09.071Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_654428e022d14e59b3531e78","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"OpenClaw channel agent binding routing configuration\",\n  \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n  \"model\": \"gemini-2.5-flash\",\n  \"tookMs\": 8461,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"content\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"08092de95bf1c543\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nOpenClaw's channel agent binding and routing configuration establishes how incoming messages from various communication channels are directed to specific agents. This routing mechanism is deterministic, ensuring that replies are sent back to the originating channel and that a consistent agent handles a given message based on predefined rules.\\n\\nKey terms in this configuration include:\\n*   **Channel**: Refers to the communication platform (e.g., WhatsApp, Telegram, Discord, Slack, Signal, iMessage, Webchat).\\n*   **AccountId**: Represents a specific per-channel account instance.\\n*   **AgentId**: Identifies an isolated workspace and session store, essentially an independent \\\"brain\\\" for processing.\\n*   **SessionKey**: The key used for storing context and managing concurrency.\\n\\n**Routing Mechanism**\\n\\nOpenClaw uses \\\"bindings\\\" to map an inbound channel, `accountId`, and peer/guild information to a specific `agentId`. The system prioritizes the most specific binding when determining which agent should handle a message. For instance, a binding explicitly configured for a particular Discord guild and channel will take precedence over a binding set for just that guild.\\n\\n**Routing Rules**\\n\\nOpenClaw employs several routing rules to select an agent for each inbound message, including:\\n*   **Exact peer match**: Based on `bindings` with `peer.kind` and `peer.id`.\\n*   **Parent peer match**: For thread inheritance.\\n*   **Guild + roles match (Discord)**: Using `guildId` and `roles`.\\n*   **Guild match (Discord)**: Using `guildId`.\\n*   **Team match (Slack)**: Using `teamId`.\\n*   **Account match**: Based on `accountId` on the channel.\\n*   **Channel match**: Any account on that channel, indicated by `accountId: \\\"*\\\" `.\\n*   **Default agent**: If no other rule applies, it falls back to a default agent defined in `agents.list[].default`, or the first entry in the agent list, then to the main agent.\\n\\nWhen a binding includes multiple matching fields (e.g., `peer`, `guildId`, `teamId`, `roles`), all specified fields must match for that binding to be applied. The matched agent then dictates which workspace and session store are utilized.\\n\\n**Configuration**\\n\\nThe core configuration for routing involves:\\n*   **`agents.list`**: Defines named agents, including their workspace and model.\\n*   **`bindings`**: Maps inbound channels, accounts, or peers to specific agents.\\n\\nYou can manage these routing rules interactively using CLI commands like `openclaw agents bindings`, `openclaw agents bind`, and `openclaw agents unbind`.\\n\\n**Binding Scope Behavior**\\n\\nBindings can be configured with different scopes:\\n*   A binding without an `accountId` will match only the channel's default account.\\n*   Using `accountId: \\\"*\\\"` provides a channel-wide fallback for all accounts, but is less specific than an explicit account binding.\\n*   If an agent already has a channel binding without an `accountId`, and a more specific binding with an explicit or resolved `accountId` is added later, OpenClaw will upgrade the existing binding in place.\\n\\n**Broadcast Groups**\\n\\nOpenClaw also supports \\\"broadcast groups,\\\" which allow multiple agents to run concurrently for the same peer, particularly useful in scenarios like WhatsApp groups after mentions or activation gating. This is configured with a `broadcast` strategy, often `parallel`, and specifies which agents should respond to specific channel/peer combinations.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"08092de95bf1c543\\\">>>\",\n  \"citations\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://docs.openclaw.ai/channels/channel-routing\",\n      \"title\": \"openclaw.ai\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://lumadock.com/tutorials/openclaw-multi-agent-coordination-governance\",\n      \"title\": \"lumadock.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://docs.openclaw.ai/cli/channels\",\n      \"title\": \"openclaw.ai\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://docs.openclaw.ai/cli/agents\",\n      \"title\": \"openclaw.ai\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"OpenClaw channel agent binding routing configuration","provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-2.5-flash","tookMs":8461,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"gemini","wrapped":true},"content":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"08092de95bf1c543\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nOpenClaw's channel agent binding and routing configuration establishes how incoming messages from various communication channels are directed to specific agents. This routing mechanism is deterministic, ensuring that replies are sent back to the originating channel and that a consistent agent handles a given message based on predefined rules.\n\nKey terms in this configuration include:\n*   **Channel**: Refers to the communication platform (e.g., WhatsApp, Telegram, Discord, Slack, Signal, iMessage, Webchat).\n*   **AccountId**: Represents a specific per-channel account instance.\n*   **AgentId**: Identifies an isolated workspace and session store, essentially an independent \"brain\" for processing.\n*   **SessionKey**: The key used for storing context and managing concurrency.\n\n**Routing Mechanism**\n\nOpenClaw uses \"bindings\" to map an inbound channel, `accountId`, and peer/guild information to a specific `agentId`. The system prioritizes the most specific binding when determining which agent should handle a message. For instance, a binding explicitly configured for a particular Discord guild and channel will take precedence over a binding set for just that guild.\n\n**Routing Rules**\n\nOpenClaw employs several routing rules to select an agent for each inbound message, including:\n*   **Exact peer match**: Based on `bindings` with `peer.kind` and `peer.id`.\n*   **Parent peer match**: For thread inheritance.\n*   **Guild + roles match (Discord)**: Using `guildId` and `roles`.\n*   **Guild match (Discord)**: Using `guildId`.\n*   **Team match (Slack)**: Using `teamId`.\n*   **Account match**: Based on `accountId` on the channel.\n*   **Channel match**: Any account on that channel, indicated by `accountId: \"*\" `.\n*   **Default agent**: If no other rule applies, it falls back to a default agent defined in `agents.list[].default`, or the first entry in the agent list, then to the main agent.\n\nWhen a binding includes multiple matching fields (e.g., `peer`, `guildId`, `teamId`, `roles`), all specified fields must match for that binding to be applied. The matched agent then dictates which workspace and session store are utilized.\n\n**Configuration**\n\nThe core configuration for routing involves:\n*   **`agents.list`**: Defines named agents, including their workspace and model.\n*   **`bindings`**: Maps inbound channels, accounts, or peers to specific agents.\n\nYou can manage these routing rules interactively using CLI commands like `openclaw agents bindings`, `openclaw agents bind`, and `openclaw agents unbind`.\n\n**Binding Scope Behavior**\n\nBindings can be configured with different scopes:\n*   A binding without an `accountId` will match only the channel's default account.\n*   Using `accountId: \"*\"` provides a channel-wide fallback for all accounts, but is less specific than an explicit account binding.\n*   If an agent already has a channel binding without an 